<Base title="About — Suryakant Kashyap" description="AI engineer with a systems background. How I came at AI from the infrastructure side, and how the two halves connect.">
  <article class="prose-post">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight mb-6">About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm an AI engineer with a systems background — currently a senior software engineer at <a href="https://www.kloudfuse.com/">Kloudfuse</a>. The day job is the metrics query path: a Prometheus-compatible API that fronts Apache Pinot. A growing slice of the day job, and most of the side work, is the LLM layer on top — retrieval pipelines, eval harnesses, prompt iteration, the operational realities of running language models against real customer data.
    </p>

    <p>
      I came at AI from the systems side rather than the other direction. In 2023 I built <a href="/posts/aida-natural-language-to-promql/">AIDA</a> — a natural-language-to-PromQL interface backed by three LLMs in parallel — when "RAG" wasn't a household term yet. That prototype taught me what every AI engineer eventually learns: the model is the easy part. Retrieval quality, eval coverage, prompt iteration loop, inference cost, latency budget — those are where the system either earns its keep or doesn't.
    </p>

    <p>
      Before AIDA and Kloudfuse I worked across a few observability and platform-engineering teams. The through-line has always been the same: production systems that emit a lot of data and need to keep that data both useful and affordable. The fun part is that the constraints — both AI-product constraints and observability constraints — push you back into the same fundamentals: what does the user actually want, what does it cost to give them, and how do you keep the answer honest.
    </p>

    <h2>How I think about the work</h2>

    <p>
      I'm drawn to systems where the abstraction is leaking on purpose — where you have to understand the storage, the query engine, and the user-facing semantics together to get anything right. LLM products and observability platforms are both like that almost by definition. The pretty answer that comes out of the model — or the dashboard — depends on retrieval shape, context window budget, bucket alignment, label cardinality, and a half-dozen other things the user shouldn't have to think about. But somebody does.
    </p>

    <p>
      My approach: read the code, write down the model, then test the model against production reality. The posts on this site are the "write down the model" step. If a post reads like a tutorial, that's me having had to learn it the hard way once.
    </p>

    <h2>Off-hours</h2>

    <p>
      Long walks, espresso, mechanical keyboards, the occasional small open-source contribution. I read more than I write. Most of what I write that isn't code ends up here.
    </p>

